properties.Title: Freezing Rain Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Freezing rain expected this evening. Light to moderate snow currently over the area is forecast to transition to a period of freezing rain or rain near Lake Ontario and the St. Lawrence river or continue as snow in areas further north. Several hours of freezing rain are expected this evening before the freezing rain changes to rain or snow tonight. Total snowfall amounts of 5 to 15 cm are possible by late Thursday in areas where the precipitation falls primarily as snow. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become icy and slippery. Freezing rain warnings are issued when rain falling in sub-zero temperatures creates ice build-up and icy surfaces. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A major low pressure system will affect Eastern Quebec on Thursday and on Friday. This system will bring heavy snow to these regions, with more than 25 to 35 cm expected over some areas of the Gaspé Peninsula. The Lower North Shore areas should receive around 15 centimetres. In addition, the strong winds combined with the snow will give near zero visibilities in blowing snow, especially over areas near the St Lawrence, the Chaleur Bay and the Lower North Shore. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Poor weather conditions may contribute to transportation delays. There may be a significant impact on rush hour traffic in urban areas. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.

properties.Title: Snow Squall Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Lake effect snow squalls with widespread blowing snow possible Thursday afternoon through Saturday. Conditions are favourable for snow squalls to develop off Lake Huron Thursday afternoon. A couple of these snow squalls may become particularly intense causing heavy snow and blowing snow well inland of Lake Huron and Georgian Bay. While the snow squalls will move with time, this snow squall event is expected to last until Saturday morning. Travel will become hazardous, and people are advised to consider changing their travel plans accordingly. ### Snow squalls cause weather conditions to vary considerably; changes from clear skies to heavy snow within just a few kilometres are common. Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow and ice pellets becoming mixed with rain Thursday night. Total snowfall: 10 to 15 cm. Maximum wind gusts: easterly 80 km/h. Locations: all of Prince Edward Island, with greatest snowfall amounts expected over Prince County. Time span: Thursday afternoon through Friday morning. Remarks: Snow will develop across the island late Thursday afternoon and will likely mix with or change to ice pellets and rain for a time on Thursday evening, especially over Queens and Kings counties. Precipitation will taper to a few flurries or showers on Friday morning. Strong easterly winds will also develop Thursday afternoon and evening, giving reduced visibilities in blowing snow for some locations. Motorists should anticipate poor driving conditions late in the day Thursday and Thursday night, possibly carrying over into Friday morning in some areas. In addition, strong easterly winds will cause higher than normal water levels along the northern coast during high tide Thursday evening and Thursday night. Ice rafting is also possible along some east- facing parts of the coast. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to PEstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #PEStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant snow and wind are expected Thursday night. Total snowfall: 5 to 15 cm except possibly higher over Cape Breton Maximum wind gusts: easterly 60 to 80 km/h and possibly higher, with Les Suetes wind gusts up to 140 km/h likely over western Cape Breton Island. Locations: northeastern mainland Nova Scotia and Cape Breton. Time span: Thursday evening until early Friday morning. Remarks: Snow and ice pellets will develop over northeastern Nova Scotia Thursday afternoon and over Cape Breton Thursday evening. Precipitation should end or taper to flurries by Friday morning. Strong easterly winds will also develop Thursday afternoon and evening, potentially giving reduced visibilities in blowing snow in some locations. A Les Suetes wind warning has been issued for Inverness County - Mabou and North, and it is possible that wind warnings will be issued for other regions of eastern Nova Scotia as the event approaches. The timing of the snow could cause poor travel conditions in the late afternoon or evening on Thursday. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.
